Change-Id: I60e43fd0204bc513df25836853ed313a56aecc1e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/0b2f0c40644133f85425155d0a27b9d60e0b0303"},{"sha":"72499dfa3a7302e296a42f6751a326bc3c3b20dc","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Add a MicroPrintf function that is independant of the ErrorReporter.

Additionally,
  * remove the global error reporter from micro_test.h
  * change all the kernel tests to make use of MicroPrintf
  * add a GetMicroErrorReporter() function that returns a pointer to a
    singleton MicroErrorReporter object.
      - This enables the current change to not spread beyond the tests.
      - Even if we move large parts of the TFLM code to make use
        MicroPrintf (in favor of error_reporter), there is still going to
        be shared TfLite/TFLM code that will need an error_reporter.

Next steps, if we want to continue down this path
  * remove the error_reporter from the TFLM functions and class
    implementations and instead use either MicroPrintf or
    GetMicroErrorReporter()
  * Add new APIs that do not have error_reporter to the TFLM classes and
    functions.
  * Ask users to switch to the new error_reporter-free APIs and
    depreacte the APIs that do make use of the error_reporter.
  * Remove the error_reporter APIs completely.

Prior to this change, we would have to use the ErrorReporter interface
for all the logging.

This was problematic on a few fronts:
 * The name ErrorReporter was often misleading since sometimes we just
   want to log, even when there isn't an error.
 * For even the simplest logging, we need to have access to an
   ErrorReporter object which means that pointers to an ErrorReporter
   are part of most classes in TFLM.

With this change, we can simply call MicroPrintf(), and it can be a no-op
if binary size is important.

If we find this approach useful, we can consider incrementally reducing
the usage of ErrorReporter from TFLM.

Progress towards http://b/158205789

starting to address review comments.

Change-Id: I2ff65489edb2ea5959259d3d22067977d681bfb7","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/adcdafc98442ccf7475187221714c5020d245981"},{"sha":"a5d38592ce513d4a77d27397455ebeb02bc67549","author":{"name":"Stephan Lee","email":"96f5b42669bb997c29f16ce474a1afad8da33a29@google.com"},"message":"Change API contract for the private add_function_callback and allow graph edits before finalizing a func_graph.

Currently, function_callbacks were invoked after the graphs were finalized, primarily used to prevent dereferencing. While the API seemingly allow graph edits, they are futile as the graph is already committed to the C++.

With this change, we change the semantics of the API a little bit and explicitly allows graph edits.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355878955
Change-Id: I60e43fd0204bc513df25836853ed313a56aecc1e","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/0b2f0c40644133f85425155d0a27b9d60e0b0303"},{"sha":"72499dfa3a7302e296a42f6751a326bc3c3b20dc","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Add a MicroPrintf function that is independant of the ErrorReporter.

Additionally,
  * remove the global error reporter from micro_test.h
  * change all the kernel tests to make use of MicroPrintf
  * add a GetMicroErrorReporter() function that returns a pointer to a
    singleton MicroErrorReporter object.
      - This enables the current change to not spread beyond the tests.
      - Even if we move large parts of the TFLM code to make use
        MicroPrintf (in favor of error_reporter), there is still going to
        be shared TfLite/TFLM code that will need an error_reporter.

Next steps, if we want to continue down this path
  * remove the error_reporter from the TFLM functions and class
    implementations and instead use either MicroPrintf or
    GetMicroErrorReporter()
  * Add new APIs that do not have error_reporter to the TFLM classes and
    functions.
  * Ask users to switch to the new error_reporter-free APIs and
    depreacte the APIs that do make use of the error_reporter.
  * Remove the error_reporter APIs completely.

Prior to this change, we would have to use the ErrorReporter interface
for all the logging.

This was problematic on a few fronts:
 * The name ErrorReporter was often misleading since sometimes we just
   want to log, even when there isn't an error.
 * For even the simplest logging, we need to have access to an
   ErrorReporter object which means that pointers to an ErrorReporter
   are part of most classes in TFLM.

With this change, we can simply call MicroPrintf(), and it can be a no-op
if binary size is important.

If we find this approach useful, we can consider incrementally reducing
the usage of ErrorReporter from TFLM.

Progress towards http://b/158205789

starting to address review comments.

re-do micro_test.h","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/72499dfa3a7302e296a42f6751a326bc3c3b20dc"}]

Change-Id: Ibad02cee524e744bb6ef7f50a52e4d27030ac4c0","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/581a3825f85cb910890ec25983d22a68e0ec8dca"},{"sha":"a0bd36e7f47f1e0305d8577096e1660ca1c9aa4f","author":{"name":"Revan Sopher","email":"fd8618e46eba31404d9f9c653310103aea3024f0@google.com"},"message":"Support passing and returning Nones in TPUStrategy.

This is supported in non-TPU strategies, and surprises users trying to migrate.
The lower-level input and output replication ops can't handle values that aren't convertible to Tensor, so we need to do some massaging around this. Nones in inputs are temporarily replaced with a constant, then replaced after replication. Nones in outputs are simply not replicated, as output replication happens at a per-value granularity.

Signed-off-by: Jakub Dyszkiewicz <jakub.dyszkiewicz@gmail.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kumahq/kuma/commits/f0579d927b1ceb24ab2734b77c4ce84cded794e1"},{"sha":"47cda6685c908bedacee11002b66e989ccc70894","author":{"name":"Bart Smykla","email":"1510bcc82b444bd3d94fed33ba1fa2e72fc0e429@smykla.com"},"message":"feat(kumactl) add kumactl install crds cmd (#1419)

* feat(kumactl) add kumactl install crds cmd

- Introduced new `kumactl` command: `kumactl install crds`
  which will render all Custom Resource Definitions used by kuma.
  By providing `--only-missing` flag it will output content of
  CRDs which are not present in the cluster (it will use the same
  approach to get kubeconfig as `kumactl install control-plane`
  - I added small script which I will be using in helm hooks
    to generate missing CRDs. I'm doing it via script, and not by
    directly providing `entrypoint` or `cmd` to container, as there
    is logic to check if command `kumactl install crds \
     --only-missing` returns anything as if there are already
    all CRDs present the command `kubectl create -f -` would fail
    and I don't see any other, easier way to handle this case
- Added helm's pre-upgrade hook to install missing crds, which is
  using the container with `kumactl` mentioned above
- Modified helm's `values.yaml` file to reflect changes mentioned
  above

* fix(kumactl) fix sh scripts (removed function key)

Updated .golden files to reflect the new command
`kumactl install crds`

* feat(*) add helm upgrade logic to e2e framework

Introduced to our e2e tests framework functionalities to upgrade
kuma helm charts.

* fix(*) add helm repo for kuma in CI

As we currently are using our external helm repository, to install
some older versions of Kuma during the helm upgrade tests,
we have to configure helm to use this repository first

* feat(kumactl) introuce ctx to install crds command

in an "index out of range".

This bug was introduced in the original implementation in 1756af6fafabd9197feb56c0324e49dd7d30b11f,
but was not reproducible when using the CLI, because the same commit also added
client-side validation on the flag before making an API request. The following
example, uses an invalid rule (`c *:*  rwm` - two spaces before the permissions);

```console
$ docker run --rm --network=host --device-cgroup-rule='c *:*  rwm' busybox
invalid argument "c *:*  rwm" for "--device-cgroup-rule" flag: invalid device cgroup format 'c *:*  rwm'
```

Doing the same, but using the API results in a daemon panic when starting the container;

Create a container with an invalid device cgroup rule:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/create?name=foobar" \
  -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
  -d '{"Image":"busybox:latest", "HostConfig":{"DeviceCgroupRules": ["c *:*  rwm"]}}'
```

Start the container:

```console
curl -v \
  --unix-socket /var/run/docker.sock \
  -X POST \
  "http://localhost/v1.41/containers/foobar/start"
```

Observe the daemon logs:

```
2021-01-22 12:53:03.313806 I | http: panic serving @: runtime error: index out of range [0] with length 0
goroutine 571 [running]:
net/http.(*conn).serve.func1(0xc000cb2d20)
	/usr/local/go/src/net/http/server.go:1795 +0x13b
panic(0x2f32380, 0xc000aebfc0)
	/usr/local/go/src/runtime/panic.go:679 +0x1b6
github.com/docker/docker/oci.AppendDevicePermissionsFromCgroupRules(0xc000175c00, 0x8, 0x8, 0xc0000bd380, 0x1, 0x4, 0x0, 0x0, 0xc0000e69c0, 0x0, ...)
	/go/src/github.com/docker/docker/oci/oci.go:34 +0x64f
```

This patch:

- fixes the panic, allowing the daemon to return an error on container start
- adds a unit-test to validate various permutations
- adds a "todo" to verify the regular expression (and handling) of the "a" (all) value

We should also consider performing this validation when _creating_ the container,
so that an error is produced early.

[{"sha":"c62672196f854d933a5eccf83149911895180b5a","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Add a MicroPrintf function that is independant of the ErrorReporter.

Additionally,
  * remove the global error reporter from micro_test.h
  * change all the kernel tests to make use of MicroPrintf
  * add a GetMicroErrorReporter() function that returns a pointer to a
    singleton MicroErrorReporter object.
      - This enables the current change to not spread beyond the tests.
      - Even if we move large parts of the TFLM code to make use
        MicroPrintf (in favor of error_reporter), there is still going to
        be shared TfLite/TFLM code that will need an error_reporter.

Next steps, if we want to continue down this path
  * remove the error_reporter from the TFLM functions and class
    implementations and instead use either MicroPrintf or
    GetMicroErrorReporter()
  * Add new APIs that do not have error_reporter to the TFLM classes and
    functions.
  * Ask users to switch to the new error_reporter-free APIs and
    depreacte the APIs that do make use of the error_reporter.
  * Remove the error_reporter APIs completely.

Prior to this change, we would have to use the ErrorReporter interface
for all the logging.

This was problematic on a few fronts:
 * The name ErrorReporter was often misleading since sometimes we just
   want to log, even when there isn't an error.
 * For even the simplest logging, we need to have access to an
   ErrorReporter object which means that pointers to an ErrorReporter
   are part of most classes in TFLM.

With this change, we can simply call MicroPrintf(), and it can be a no-op
if binary size is important.

If we find this approach useful, we can consider incrementally reducing
the usage of ErrorReporter from TFLM.

Progress towards http://b/158205789

starting to address review comments.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/c62672196f854d933a5eccf83149911895180b5a"}]

Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Workaround for a LLVM crash when doing codegen for MLIR generated Cast kernel

When you enable (uncomment) the `gen_kernel_library` rule for `cast` in `tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/BUILD`, the build would fail on the ROCm platform with the following error

```
LLVM ERROR: Cannot select: 0x56134e3c5b10: i1 = fp_to_sint 0x56134d1f53d8
  0x56134d1f53d8: f16 = bitcast 0x56134e3c58a0
    0x56134e3c58a0: i16,ch = load<(load 2 from %ir.lsr.iv)> 0x56134eaa3788, 0x56134e3c5698, undef:i64
      0x56134e3c5698: i64,ch = CopyFromReg 0x56134eaa3788, Register:i64 %16
        0x56134d41d620: i64 = Register %16
      0x56134d1f5850: i64 = undef
In function: Cast_f16_i1_kernel
TensorFlow crashed, please file a bug on https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues with the trace below.
Stack dump:
0.	Program arguments: bazel-out/host/bin/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tools/kernel_gen/tf_to_kernel --unroll_factors=4 --tile_sizes=256 --arch=gfx803,gfx900,gfx906,gfx908 --input=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1.mlir --output=bazel-out/k8-opt/bin/tensorflow/core/kernels/mlir_generated/cast_f16_i1_kernel_generator_kernel.o --enable_ftz=False
1.	2.	Running pass 'CallGraph Pass Manager' on module 'acme'.
3.	Running pass 'AMDGPU DAG->DAG Pattern Instruction Selection' on function '@Cast_f16_i1_kernel'
...
...
```

Jack (@whchung) identified the root cause of this crash as lack of support for FPTOSI (fp16 to i1) instruction in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. The correct fix for this bug, is to add support for the same in the AMDGPU LLVM backend. Jack is in the process of upstreaming that fix to the LLVM repo.

Change-Id: I2ff65489edb2ea5959259d3d22067977d681bfb7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/adcdafc98442ccf7475187221714c5020d245981"},{"sha":"a5d38592ce513d4a77d27397455ebeb02bc67549","author":{"name":"Stephan Lee","email":"96f5b42669bb997c29f16ce474a1afad8da33a29@google.com"},"message":"Change API contract for the private add_function_callback and allow graph edits before finalizing a func_graph.

Currently, function_callbacks were invoked after the graphs were finalized, primarily used to prevent dereferencing. While the API seemingly allow graph edits, they are futile as the graph is already committed to the C++.

With this change, we change the semantics of the API a little bit and explicitly allows graph edits.

Change-Id: I60e43fd0204bc513df25836853ed313a56aecc1e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/0b2f0c40644133f85425155d0a27b9d60e0b0303"},{"sha":"72499dfa3a7302e296a42f6751a326bc3c3b20dc","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Add a MicroPrintf function that is independant of the ErrorReporter.

Additionally,
  * remove the global error reporter from micro_test.h
  * change all the kernel tests to make use of MicroPrintf
  * add a GetMicroErrorReporter() function that returns a pointer to a
    singleton MicroErrorReporter object.
      - This enables the current change to not spread beyond the tests.
      - Even if we move large parts of the TFLM code to make use
        MicroPrintf (in favor of error_reporter), there is still going to
        be shared TfLite/TFLM code that will need an error_reporter.

Next steps, if we want to continue down this path
  * remove the error_reporter from the TFLM functions and class
    implementations and instead use either MicroPrintf or
    GetMicroErrorReporter()
  * Add new APIs that do not have error_reporter to the TFLM classes and
    functions.
  * Ask users to switch to the new error_reporter-free APIs and
    depreacte the APIs that do make use of the error_reporter.
  * Remove the error_reporter APIs completely.

Prior to this change, we would have to use the ErrorReporter interface
for all the logging.

This was problematic on a few fronts:
 * The name ErrorReporter was often misleading since sometimes we just
   want to log, even when there isn't an error.
 * For even the simplest logging, we need to have access to an
   ErrorReporter object which means that pointers to an ErrorReporter
   are part of most classes in TFLM.

With this change, we can simply call MicroPrintf(), and it can be a no-op
if binary size is important.

If we find this approach useful, we can consider incrementally reducing
the usage of ErrorReporter from TFLM.

Progress towards http://b/158205789

starting to address review comments.

Currently, function_callbacks were invoked after the graphs were finalized, primarily used to prevent dereferencing. While the API seemingly allow graph edits, they are futile as the graph is already committed to the C++.

With this change, we change the semantics of the API a little bit and explicitly allows graph edits.

Change-Id: I60e43fd0204bc513df25836853ed313a56aecc1e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/0b2f0c40644133f85425155d0a27b9d60e0b0303"},{"sha":"72499dfa3a7302e296a42f6751a326bc3c3b20dc","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Add a MicroPrintf function that is independant of the ErrorReporter.

Additionally,
  * remove the global error reporter from micro_test.h
  * change all the kernel tests to make use of MicroPrintf
  * add a GetMicroErrorReporter() function that returns a pointer to a
    singleton MicroErrorReporter object.
      - This enables the current change to not spread beyond the tests.
      - Even if we move large parts of the TFLM code to make use
        MicroPrintf (in favor of error_reporter), there is still going to
        be shared TfLite/TFLM code that will need an error_reporter.

Next steps, if we want to continue down this path
  * remove the error_reporter from the TFLM functions and class
    implementations and instead use either MicroPrintf or
    GetMicroErrorReporter()
  * Add new APIs that do not have error_reporter to the TFLM classes and
    functions.
  * Ask users to switch to the new error_reporter-free APIs and
    depreacte the APIs that do make use of the error_reporter.
  * Remove the error_reporter APIs completely.

Prior to this change, we would have to use the ErrorReporter interface
for all the logging.

This was problematic on a few fronts:
 * The name ErrorReporter was often misleading since sometimes we just
   want to log, even when there isn't an error.
 * For even the simplest logging, we need to have access to an
   ErrorReporter object which means that pointers to an ErrorReporter
   are part of most classes in TFLM.

With this change, we can simply call MicroPrintf(), and it can be a no-op
if binary size is important.

If we find this approach useful, we can consider incrementally reducing
the usage of ErrorReporter from TFLM.

Progress towards http://b/158205789

starting to address review comments.

Currently, function_callbacks were invoked after the graphs were finalized, primarily used to prevent dereferencing. While the API seemingly allow graph edits, they are futile as the graph is already committed to the C++.

With this change, we change the semantics of the API a little bit and explicitly allows graph edits.

Change-Id: I60e43fd0204bc513df25836853ed313a56aecc1e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/0b2f0c40644133f85425155d0a27b9d60e0b0303"},{"sha":"72499dfa3a7302e296a42f6751a326bc3c3b20dc","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Add a MicroPrintf function that is independant of the ErrorReporter.

Additionally,
  * remove the global error reporter from micro_test.h
  * change all the kernel tests to make use of MicroPrintf
  * add a GetMicroErrorReporter() function that returns a pointer to a
    singleton MicroErrorReporter object.
      - This enables the current change to not spread beyond the tests.
      - Even if we move large parts of the TFLM code to make use
        MicroPrintf (in favor of error_reporter), there is still going to
        be shared TfLite/TFLM code that will need an error_reporter.

Next steps, if we want to continue down this path
  * remove the error_reporter from the TFLM functions and class
    implementations and instead use either MicroPrintf or
    GetMicroErrorReporter()
  * Add new APIs that do not have error_reporter to the TFLM classes and
    functions.
  * Ask users to switch to the new error_reporter-free APIs and
    depreacte the APIs that do make use of the error_reporter.
  * Remove the error_reporter APIs completely.

Prior to this change, we would have to use the ErrorReporter interface
for all the logging.

This was problematic on a few fronts:
 * The name ErrorReporter was often misleading since sometimes we just
   want to log, even when there isn't an error.
 * For even the simplest logging, we need to have access to an
   ErrorReporter object which means that pointers to an ErrorReporter
   are part of most classes in TFLM.

With this change, we can simply call MicroPrintf(), and it can be a no-op
if binary size is important.

If we find this approach useful, we can consider incrementally reducing
the usage of ErrorReporter from TFLM.

Progress towards http://b/158205789

starting to address review comments.

[{"sha":"d7613a0aac1f42f9e05e9d9c3a3d9d53b554ddfa","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Better diagnostics for apply positional args

The previous changes removing support for using the trailing positional
argument as a working directory missed a spot in the apply/destroy
command implementation. We still support this argument for applying a
saved plan:

    terraform apply foo.tfplan

However, if you pass a positional path which doesn't "look like" a plan
(for example, the path to a configuration directory), Terraform would
silently ignore it and continue.

This commit fixes that by adding an error message if the user specifies
a path which the plan loader rejects as not "looking like" a plan. This
message includes a reference to the `-chdir` flag as a pointer about
what to do next.

We also rearrange the error message when calling `terraform destroy`
with a plan file argument, and add test coverage for the above. While
we're here, update the destroy tests to copy the fixture directory,
chdir, and defer cleanup.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pecigonzalo/terraform/commits/d7613a0aac1f42f9e05e9d9c3a3d9d53b554ddfa"},{"sha":"32d20843878c3aa8f7dc1e0926f74c130bdc9e50","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27679 from hashicorp/alisdair/apply-destroy-test-fixes

Change-Id: I60e43fd0204bc513df25836853ed313a56aecc1e","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Nicholas282787728/tensorflow/commits/0b2f0c40644133f85425155d0a27b9d60e0b0303"},{"sha":"72499dfa3a7302e296a42f6751a326bc3c3b20dc","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Add a MicroPrintf function that is independant of the ErrorReporter.

Additionally,
  * remove the global error reporter from micro_test.h
  * change all the kernel tests to make use of MicroPrintf
  * add a GetMicroErrorReporter() function that returns a pointer to a
    singleton MicroErrorReporter object.
      - This enables the current change to not spread beyond the tests.
      - Even if we move large parts of the TFLM code to make use
        MicroPrintf (in favor of error_reporter), there is still going to
        be shared TfLite/TFLM code that will need an error_reporter.

Next steps, if we want to continue down this path
  * remove the error_reporter from the TFLM functions and class
    implementations and instead use either MicroPrintf or
    GetMicroErrorReporter()
  * Add new APIs that do not have error_reporter to the TFLM classes and
    functions.
  * Ask users to switch to the new error_reporter-free APIs and
    depreacte the APIs that do make use of the error_reporter.
  * Remove the error_reporter APIs completely.

Prior to this change, we would have to use the ErrorReporter interface
for all the logging.

This was problematic on a few fronts:
 * The name ErrorReporter was often misleading since sometimes we just
   want to log, even when there isn't an error.
 * For even the simplest logging, we need to have access to an
   ErrorReporter object which means that pointers to an ErrorReporter
   are part of most classes in TFLM.

With this change, we can simply call MicroPrintf(), and it can be a no-op
if binary size is important.

If we find this approach useful, we can consider incrementally reducing
the usage of ErrorReporter from TFLM.

Progress towards http://b/158205789

starting to address review comments.

With this change, we change the semantics of the API a little bit and explicitly allows graph edits.

[{"sha":"72499dfa3a7302e296a42f6751a326bc3c3b20dc","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Add a MicroPrintf function that is independant of the ErrorReporter.

Additionally,
  * remove the global error reporter from micro_test.h
  * change all the kernel tests to make use of MicroPrintf
  * add a GetMicroErrorReporter() function that returns a pointer to a
    singleton MicroErrorReporter object.
      - This enables the current change to not spread beyond the tests.
      - Even if we move large parts of the TFLM code to make use
        MicroPrintf (in favor of error_reporter), there is still going to
        be shared TfLite/TFLM code that will need an error_reporter.

Next steps, if we want to continue down this path
  * remove the error_reporter from the TFLM functions and class
    implementations and instead use either MicroPrintf or
    GetMicroErrorReporter()
  * Add new APIs that do not have error_reporter to the TFLM classes and
    functions.
  * Ask users to switch to the new error_reporter-free APIs and
    depreacte the APIs that do make use of the error_reporter.
  * Remove the error_reporter APIs completely.

Prior to this change, we would have to use the ErrorReporter interface
for all the logging.

This was problematic on a few fronts:
 * The name ErrorReporter was often misleading since sometimes we just
   want to log, even when there isn't an error.
 * For even the simplest logging, we need to have access to an
   ErrorReporter object which means that pointers to an ErrorReporter
   are part of most classes in TFLM.

With this change, we can simply call MicroPrintf(), and it can be a no-op
if binary size is important.

If we find this approach useful, we can consider incrementally reducing
the usage of ErrorReporter from TFLM.

[{"sha":"d7613a0aac1f42f9e05e9d9c3a3d9d53b554ddfa","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Better diagnostics for apply positional args

The previous changes removing support for using the trailing positional
argument as a working directory missed a spot in the apply/destroy
command implementation. We still support this argument for applying a
saved plan:

    terraform apply foo.tfplan

However, if you pass a positional path which doesn't "look like" a plan
(for example, the path to a configuration directory), Terraform would
silently ignore it and continue.

This commit fixes that by adding an error message if the user specifies
a path which the plan loader rejects as not "looking like" a plan. This
message includes a reference to the `-chdir` flag as a pointer about
what to do next.

We also rearrange the error message when calling `terraform destroy`
with a plan file argument, and add test coverage for the above. While
we're here, update the destroy tests to copy the fixture directory,
chdir, and defer cleanup.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/terraform/commits/d7613a0aac1f42f9e05e9d9c3a3d9d53b554ddfa"},{"sha":"32d20843878c3aa8f7dc1e0926f74c130bdc9e50","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27679 from hashicorp/alisdair/apply-destroy-test-fixes
